South Africa might see coronavirus vaccine trials starting later this year. That's according to South African Medical Research Council president and CEO Dr Glenda Gray. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - South Africa might see coronavirus vaccine trials starting later this year. That's according to South African Medical Research Council president and CEO Dr Glenda Gray. READ: SA participates in COVID-19 treatment trial “The initial trial will happen in the US and we hope to start our trials after that ...around October/November,” Gray said. Gray said South Africa is well equipped to carry out these trials. READ: COVID-19 vaccine could take a while: public health expert She added that before the trial begins, it's safety will have to established preclinically. About 20, 000 participants worldwide will be part of the trial. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.